Yeah, two things, Me From the Past: One, uh,
contemporary climate change is real. Uh, two,

00:00:14.099 --> 00:00:18.200
this isn't the first time the world has experienced
disruptive climate change, believe it or not.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:30.539
So, climate change, of course, can be a very
controversial topic, at least here in the

00:00:30.539 --> 00:00:35.000
US, but we're not discussing today whether
contemporary climate change is caused by human

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:40.180
activity, although it is. We're talking about
history, and history is never controversial.

00:00:40.180 --> 00:00:44.890
We know that climate change can happen because
it has happened. In fact, although we're living

00:00:44.890 --> 00:00:49.790
in an age of global warming today, for most
of the early modern period, the globe experienced

00:00:49.790 --> 00:00:53.790
cool temperatures. Some historians have called
this the Little Ice Age, which would make

00:00:53.790 --> 00:00:57.670
a great animated movie. Someone should get
on that. Anyway, good job, historians, giving

00:00:57.670 --> 00:01:02.900
something an evocative name for once. I'm
picturing a tiny little ice ball, like a snow globe.

00:01:02.930 --> 00:01:06.750
Apparently, the Earth was regular-sized back
then, but anyway, the Little Ice Age lasted

00:01:06.750 --> 00:01:10.110
from the thirteenth through the nineteenth
centuries and it was a period when average

00:01:10.110 --> 00:01:13.990
temperatures were cooler than they are now.
This doesn't mean that it was always cold,

00:01:13.990 --> 00:01:18.280
though; there were volatile shifts between
bitterly cold winters and wet summers and

00:01:18.280 --> 00:01:23.420
long droughts. Also, weather conditions were
not always the same in all parts of the world,

00:01:23.420 --> 00:01:28.920
kind of like how the winter of 2014 was terribly
cold in the United States but still one of

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:33.510
the warmest on record worldwide. Climate is
not weather.

00:01:33.510 --> 00:01:38.000
So, we know temperatures were colder partly
because of science but also because of history.

00:01:38.500 --> 00:01:42.600
Science has shown through the study of stuff
like tree rings and ice cores that it really

00:01:42.600 --> 00:01:46.060
was colder back then. But we also know this
from history. I mean, records kept at the

00:01:46.060 --> 00:01:51.460
time by monks, and wine-makers, and others
also reported cold weather and bad harvests.

00:01:51.460 --> 00:01:56.020
Bad harvests are crucial to our understanding
of the Little Ice Age because they were catastrophic

00:01:56.020 --> 00:02:00.650
events, bringing hunger and, in some cases,
starvation to millions of people. And because

00:02:00.650 --> 00:02:04.590
they were so catastrophic, people wrote about
them, which leaves us a historical record.

00:02:04.590 --> 00:02:09.319
Less food meant more disease and also more
crime. Poor harvests often led to civil unrest,

00:02:09.319 --> 00:02:13.810
especially bread riots. For some, a sensible
strategy was to hit the road or, in the case

00:02:13.810 --> 00:02:17.340
of the Norseman, hit the sea. In fact, sometime
during this period, their search for better

00:02:17.340 --> 00:02:19.170
fishing grounds led them to America.

00:02:19.170 --> 00:02:23.280
And humans also prove very innovative when
adapting to new climate extremes. One example

00:02:23.280 --> 00:02:27.220
near to my heart is the Netherlands, where
people developed water control systems and

00:02:27.220 --> 00:02:31.900
experimented with new agricultural technology
to make farms less vulnerable to terrible

00:02:31.900 --> 00:02:33.010
weather events like floods.

00:02:33.010 --> 00:02:37.090
But the Little Ice Age led to unpredictable
harvests around the world and without, like,

00:02:37.090 --> 00:02:40.879
Spam to fall back on, a couple bad harvests
in a row was fatal.

00:02:40.879 --> 00:02:45.379
So, the whole Little Ice Age was pretty bad
but the seventeenth century was the worst.

00:02:45.379 --> 00:02:49.020
Some historians even refer to it as a period
of global crisis. I mean, here are just a

00:02:49.020 --> 00:02:53.540
few examples of the political instability
in the seventeenth century: the English revolutions

00:02:53.540 --> 00:03:00.420
of 1640 and 1689, Spain's European Wars and
debt problems, peasant and urban worker uprisings

00:03:00.420 --> 00:03:05.069
in Italy, the fall of the Ming and the rise
of the Qing Dynasties in China, a succession

00:03:05.069 --> 00:03:09.239
crisis in the Ottoman Empire, wars between
colonists and Native Americans that nearly

00:03:09.239 --> 00:03:14.379
destroyed Britain's colonies, the Mughal Wars
of Succession, oh, and the Thirty Years War.

00:03:14.379 --> 00:03:18.019
And that's not even to mention Shakespeare.
No Little Ice Age, no Shakespeare. That's

00:03:18.019 --> 00:03:21.739
what I would argue. Totally a climate-dependant
writer. I would be just as good as him if

00:03:21.739 --> 00:03:23.810
only we were in a period of climate change.

00:03:23.810 --> 00:03:28.019
Now, obviously, we can't say that all of these
upheavals were caused by cooler temperatures,

00:03:28.019 --> 00:03:32.540
but they did correlate with them, and in many
cases, weather contributed to them. Unrest

00:03:32.540 --> 00:03:38.250
was often linked to food shortages and taxes.
The taxes were high and the food was short

00:03:38.250 --> 00:03:39.989
because the harvests were bad.

00:03:39.989 --> 00:03:43.750
Now, for many people in the seventeenth century,
the cause of the calamitous bad weather was

00:03:43.750 --> 00:03:49.459
obvious: human sinfulness. As Welsh historian
James Howell wrote in 1647, "God Almighty

00:03:49.459 --> 00:03:54.159
has a quarrel lately with all mankind, and
given the reins to the ill spirit to compass

00:03:54.159 --> 00:03:58.690
the whole Earth." Others blamed bad weather
on witches, always a safe bet, or on natural

00:03:58.690 --> 00:04:03.530
phenomena like eclipses, earthquakes, comets,
or sunspots. And they might not have been

00:04:03.530 --> 00:04:06.140
totally wrong. Well, they were totally wrong
about the witches, but- but there were fewer

00:04:06.140 --> 00:04:11.870
recorded sunspots, especially in 1617 and
1618, when the Thirty Years War began. Oh,

00:04:11.870 --> 00:04:17.169
and there were twelve volcanic eruptions between
1638 and 1644, which produced dust veils that

00:04:17.169 --> 00:04:19.099
might have made the whole planet cooler.

00:04:19.099 --> 00:04:21.869
The weather in the middle of the seventeenth
century, right around the time of the English

00:04:21.869 --> 00:04:27.680
Revolution, was especially bad, like in Massachusetts,
1642 was so cold that the bay froze, while

00:04:27.680 --> 00:04:32.270
in Indonesia, the droughts caused rice harvests
to fail. Much of Africa faced droughts between

00:04:32.270 --> 00:04:38.050
1640 and 1644 and in 1643, flooding in the
Low Countries was so bad that cows and chickens

00:04:38.050 --> 00:04:44.099
ended up in trees. And Scandinavia recorded
its coldest winter ever in 1641. And these

00:04:44.099 --> 00:04:49.419
changes in weather were profoundly disruptive
because much more than today, people depended

00:04:49.419 --> 00:04:53.389
directly on agriculture, and thus the weather,
for their livelihoods.

00:04:53.389 --> 00:04:55.339
Let's go to the Thought Bubble.

